Loading the data set¶

We load the Davidson et al. (2017) data set containing 24 783 tweets labeled by CrowdFlower users as hate speech, offensive language or neither.

In [2]:
df = pd.read_csv('labeled_data.csv', usecols=range(1, 7))

The data set consists of 6 columns:

  • count - the number of CrowdFlower users who labeled the tweet
  • hate_speech - the number of CrowdFlower users who labeled the tweet as hate speech
  • offensive_language - the number of CrowdFlower users who labeled the tweet as offensive language
  • neither - the number of CrowdFlower users who labeled the tweet as neither
  • class - the final label (determined by the majority of users who labeled that tweet)
  • tweet - the content of the tweet

Our focus will be on the tweet and class columns.

The class variable is categorical and uses the following encoding:

  • 0 - hate speech
  • 1 - offensive language
  • 2 - neither

The word cloud for all tweets shows that words generally used in sexist, racist, and homophobic contexts appear frequently in the data, as can be expected.

"RT" and "t co" also appear quite often, but they are Twitter-specific terms which don't seem to be useful in our case ("RT" being an abbreviation of ReTweet, and "t co" being a part of http://t.co since Twitter automatically shortens all tweet URLs to that). They will be handled during preprocessing.

Preprocessing¶

Since tweets aren't necessarily just plain text but could contain elements like URLs, mentions, symbols, emojis, and hashtags, along with Twitter-specific words like RT and FAV, we'll have to preprocess them using the preprocess method.

URLs, mentions, symbols, emojis and special words will be removed since they don't seem to be useful for our classification task.

Hashtags, on the other hand, could contain text that is relevant for a given tweet's classification, so we'll use word segmentation to split them into words. Each hashtag will then be replaced by a string of the obtained words separated by whitespaces.

In [10]:
ws.load()
In [11]:
def preprocess(tweet):
    """
    Handles common tweet elements:
    
    - URLs, mentions, symbols, emojis, and special words (RT, FAV) are removed,
    - hashtags are replaced with the words they consist of.
    """
    patterns_to_remove = {
        'url_pattern': r'https?:\/\/(www\.)?[-a-zA-Z0-9@:%._\+~#=]{1,256}\.'
                       r'[a-zA-Z0-9()]{1,6}\b([-a-zA-Z0-9()@:%_\+.~#?&//=]*)',
        'special_words_pattern': r'\b(?<![@#])(RT|FAV)\b',
        'mention_pattern': r'@[\w-]+',
        'symbol_emoji_pattern': r'&(#\d+|\w+);'
    }
    hashtag_pattern = r'#(\w+)'
    
    processed_tweet = re.sub('|'.join(patterns_to_remove.values()), '', tweet)
    processed_tweet = re.sub(hashtag_pattern,
                             lambda m: ' '.join(ws.segment(m.group())),
                             processed_tweet)
    
    return processed_tweet

Tweets will be converted to tokens based on nltk's word_tokenize. The tokens are lowercased and stemmed using nltk's PorterStemmer. Extra whitespaces, punctuation, and stopwords are removed.

In [12]:
punctuation = set(string.punctuation) | {'``', '\'\''}

stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english')) | {"i'm", "'m"}
for stopword in stopwords.words('english'):
    stop_words |= set(word_tokenize(stopword))
    
stemmer = PorterStemmer()

def tokenize(tweet):
    """
    Returns tokens obtained from the given tweet.
    
    The tokens are lowercased. Extra whitespaces, punctuation, and stopwords are removed.
    """
    tweet = re.sub(r'\s+|\.\.+', ' ', tweet)
    tokens = [stemmer.stem(word) for word in word_tokenize(tweet.lower())
              if word not in punctuation and word not in stop_words]
    
    return tokens
In [13]:
tokenized_tweets = df['tweet'].apply(preprocess).apply(tokenize)

Tweets to features¶

Tweets will be extracted to features using three different methods: Bag-of-Words, TF-IDF, and Word2Vec.

Bag-of-Word features¶

The simplest way of representing tweets as features is by encoding them as vectors of token frequencies (counts) of all the unique tokens in the data set. The frequency of a token is the number of occurrences of that token in a given tokenized tweet. In the general case, we would thus obtain a num_tweets x num_unique_tokens_in_data matrix for the data set. This representation is sparse since each tweet contains only a very small number of tokens.

We chose to limit the number of features to 10 000 (i.e. only the 10 000 highest frequencies will be taken into account), and to consider not only unigrams but also bigrams and trigrams (in other words, tokens and sequences of 2 and 3 adjacent tokens).

In [14]:
count_vect = CountVectorizer(
    tokenizer=tokenize,
    preprocessor=preprocess,
    ngram_range=(1, 3),
    max_features=10000
)

TF-IDF features¶

A more complex way of converting tweets to features is the TF-IDF method. Here we would also obtain a num_tweets x num_unique_tokens_in_data matrix for the data set (in the general case), but now both the occurences of a token in a single tweet and in the entire data set are taken into account. Such a representation is also sparse.

As before, we limited the number of features to 10 000 and used unigrams, bigrams, and trigrams.

In [15]:
tfidf_vect = TfidfVectorizer(
    tokenizer=tokenize,
    preprocessor=preprocess,
    ngram_range=(1, 3),
    use_idf=True,
    smooth_idf=False,
    norm=None,
    max_features=10000
)

Word2Vec features¶

Word2Vec is a popular method of text representation that uses a neural network model to obtain dense vectors for each token in the data set.

We chose (through trial and error) to create token vectors of length 500, ignore all tokens with under 10 total occurrences, and use a context window of size 5.

In [16]:
w2v_model = Word2Vec(
    tokenized_tweets,
    size=500,
    window=5,
    min_count=10,
    seed = 123
) 

w2v_model.train(tokenized_tweets, total_examples=len(df['tweet']), epochs=20)
Out[16]:
(2576899, 3751040)

Since each token is a vector, using them directly for tweet representation would result in a vector or vectors. This is why we'll use the average of the token vectors found in a tweet as that tweet's Word2Vec representation.

In [17]:
def w2v_tweet(tokenized_tweet, size):
    """
    Converts a tokenized tweet into a Word2Vec tweet of the given size.
    
    The Word2Vec tweet is the average of all the word2vec vectors
    of tokens found in the tweet.
    """
    vector = np.zeros(size)
    count = 0
    
    for token in tokenized_tweet:
        try:
            vector += w2v_model.wv[token]
            count += 1
        except KeyError:
            continue
        
    if count != 0:
        vector /= count
        
    return vector
In [18]:
w2v_tweets = np.zeros((len(tokenized_tweets), 500))

for i, tokenized_tweet in enumerate(tokenized_tweets):
    w2v_tweets[i, :] = w2v_tweet(tokenized_tweet, 500)

w2v_tweets.shape

(24783, 500)

Models¶

Three classification models were chosen based on their good performance on similar hate speech detection problems (Ayo et al. (2020)) $-$ Logistic Regression, Random Forest, and Gradient Boosting. Additionally, these models allow for tuning to avoid overfitting in case of high dimentional datasets, which is our case, and they are pretty simple and easy to interpret.

We chose one hyperparameter per model to tune through GridSearchCV, as this task requires a lot of computational power.

Logistic Regression¶

In [19]:
def logistic_regression_gscv(X_train, y_train, file_path='results/logreg.gscv'):
    """
    Returns GridSearchCV results for logistic regression on the given training set.
    
    The results are saved to file using the specified file_path.
    """
    pipeline = Pipeline([
        ('clf', LogisticRegression(class_weight='balanced', penalty='l2',
                                   max_iter=1000, random_state=RANDOM_STATE))
    ])

    pg = {
        'clf__C': [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10],
    }

    cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5).split(X_train, y_train)
    gscv = GridSearchCV(estimator=pipeline, param_grid=pg, cv=list(cv),
                        n_jobs=-1, verbose=2).fit(X_train, y_train)

    dump(gscv, file_path)
    
    return gscv

Random forest¶

In [20]:
def random_forest_gscv(X_train, y_train, file_path='results/rf.gscv'):
    """
    Returns GridSearchCV results for random forest on the given training set.
    
    The results are saved to file using the specified file_path.
    """
    pipeline = Pipeline([
        ('clf', RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=150, class_weight="balanced",
                                       random_state=RANDOM_STATE))
    ])

    pg = {
        'clf__max_depth': [100, 50, 20, 15, 10],
    }

    cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5).split(X_train, y_train)
    gscv = GridSearchCV(estimator=pipeline, param_grid=pg, cv=list(cv),
                        n_jobs=-1, verbose=2, scoring="recall_macro").fit(X_train, y_train)

    dump(gscv, file_path)
    
    return gscv

Gradient Boosting¶

In [21]:
def gradient_boosting_gscv(X_train, y_train, file_path='results/gb.gscv'):
    """
    Returns GridSearchCV results for gradient boosting on the given training set.
    
    The results are saved to file using the specified file_path.
    """
    pipeline = Pipeline([
        ('clf', GradientBoostingClassifier(n_estimators=150, max_depth=5, max_features=30,
                                           random_state=RANDOM_STATE))
    ])

    pg = {
        'clf__learning_rate': [1, 0.75, 0.5, 0.2, 0.15, 0.1],
    }

    cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5).split(X_train, y_train)
    gscv = GridSearchCV(estimator=pipeline, param_grid=pg, cv=list(cv),
                        n_jobs=-1, verbose=2, scoring="recall_macro").fit(X_train, y_train)

    dump(gscv, file_path)
    
    return gscv

# auxiliary function for visualizing feature importance
def plot_n_most_important_features(viz, n):
    """Uses a FeatureImportances instance to plot the n most important features."""
    data = pd.DataFrame(data=viz.feature_importances_, index=viz.features_,
                    columns=["Feature Importance"]).reset_index()
    data.rename({"index": "Feature"}, axis=1, inplace=True)
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,10))
    sns.barplot(data=data.nlargest(n, "Feature Importance"),
                x="Feature Importance", y="Feature", color="midnightblue")

Results for each combination of feature representation and classification model are shown below.

The data set was first split into training and test sets (80-20 split), after which the training set was split into 5 subsets, keeping the proportions of each label the same as for the original data set. GridSearchCV trained a model for each combination of the 5 subsets and model parameters, of which we chose to select and analyse the best found model.

Models were evaluated on the test set using standard performance metrics:

  • precision $-$ the fraction of cases where the model correctly predicted the label $l$ out of all the cases where it predicted $l$,
  • recall $-$ the fraction of cases where the model correctly predicted $l$ out of all of the cases where the label actually is $l$,
  • F1-score $-$ a weighted harmonic mean of precision and recall, where the 1.0 is the best score is 1.0 and 0.0 the worst.

These metrics were especially useful since we are dealing with an imbalanced data set. Confusion matrices were plotted to help visualize the performance.

An analysis of feature importance was performed for the Bag-of-Words and TF-IDF representations, as we can easily determine which n-gram represents a given feature and vice versa. We visualized the top 10 most important features in a bar plot.

Conclusion¶

The models seem to deliver very good results, especially when classifying "offensive language" and "neither" tweets.

The performance on "hate speech" is mediocre at best across models and representations. Gradient boosting performs quite badly here, as it often confuses "hate speech" tweets with "offensive language" tweets. The reason behind this, we assume, is the imbalanced data that we had $-$ only a few tweets had the label "hate speech", and there is a large similarity between the language used in that class and "offensive language", which makes it difficult for the models to differentiate between them.

The Logistic regression model seems to have the best performance across the representations, and Gradient boosting the worst (especially for TF-IDF and Word2Vec where it misclassifies a majority of the "hate speech" tweets). Random forest's performance is comparable to Logistic regression for Bag-of-Words and TF-IDF, but it is equally likely to classify a "hate speech" tweet as "hate speech" or as "offensive language" for Word2Vec.

The most important features always contain slurs or words frequently used in racist, sexist, and homophobic contexts, which can be expected due to the nature of the data set. Sexist slurs seems to be on top.
